caption: This was a unique and first kind of eating experience for me. I have never been to a michelin star restaurant before. Also this was the prefix menu for us so we were given lots of food to try. First we started off with a small mint tea. I don't like mint tea, but to each their own. Next we got two drinks. I don't enjoy alcohol, but my gf and friend seemed to enjoy it. Then we got to the first prefix part. Where we were given a food tower with different vegetables such as olives, radish, pickles, cabbage slaw. Also got a beet spread and humus. All of this was eaten with the given naan bread. I enjoyed most of this food. Nit the biggest fan of olives or beets so I didn't love the beet spread, but the pickled beets tasted good. The hummus was good and the rest of the platter was good. The came the meat part of the meal. We got duck and lamb. I didn't really enjoy the lamb, but the duck tasted really good. We were given more naan and sauces to eat with the meat. Two of the sauces were really good. The garlic one and the tahni. The lamb had a weird taste and felt slimy, maybe I just not a fan of lamb. The duck looked interesting but tasted really good. Was like a chewier steak. Lastly we had this chocolate dessert. And this was interesting. It was like a mulchy chocolate cheese with a sweet honey syrup thing to put on top. Poured the whole saffron honey on top loved the sweetness. The dessert was good, but not like an american dessert. This brings me to the whole experience. Was this the best food I have ever eaten? No, but that could be due to the fact I am not use to this food. I have different taste that I have grown fond of. But was it nice trying another cultures food and experiencing this restaurant. Yes. Would I come again? Probably not. It was quite expensive for me and now that I have experienced the food and haven't found it to be the most amazing food to my taste. I would like to try food at other places. The restaurant looked less open also because of covid. Lastly kinda hard to find. Its down an alley for those wondering.

Was here on a special occasion and had an all around experience. The food is amazing, the interior has an interesting design with different but somehow still matching furniture. Service was great with interesting and knowledgeable explanation of different foods, seasonings, and ways to enjoy the dish.

Absolutely delicious dishes here. We came without a reservation on Friday night, and got seated in only 5 minutes, but reservations are recommended. Their menu is diverse with several small plates using lamb, beef, duck, and fish. Their dipping sauces are difference makers, providing truly savory and spicy flavord that enhance everything. Their serve fresh bread all night. The servers were very friendly and knowledgeable about the restaurant and menu. A great experience in a very cool atmosphere. Highly recommend.

Ordered the Tawle to go mixed grill menu for four. Holy sh!t was this amazing - we've had other Michelin star takeout during the pandemic, but we haven't had anything like this. We picked up at 5, drove 45 minutes home and reheated per the instructions, and it really tasted as if it were set down in front of us at the restaurant.  Everything was perfectly seasoned, tender, moist... just... striking. This is the best take home anything I've had. Since, ever.  It ain't cheap, but I'd definitely give up three very good orders for one phenomenal meal from Maydan. I'll start cooking more at home so I can save my next order-in to be another memorable  one.
Maydan could not have been more amaZing Fight for a reservation!

We love Maydan. It's a great restaurant with great customer service and the tawle was spectacular. Celebrated a work event with some coworkers at this location and it was beyond everyone's imagination. Every dish had flavor that was outstanding and was explained well by our team of servers. The decor and vibe inside is without equal.

Equinox gave my partner and I one of the best restaurant experiences we've ever had. It was my partners birthday and the staff went above and beyond. Alfredo and Georgie took care of us and they were attentive, kind and genuinely happy we were there. We ordered the tasting menus, my partner the plant based and mine was the market menu. Every dish was absolutely outstanding. The curried pumpkin soup was my favorite but everything was 5star quality. Will definitely return and will be talking about our evening for a while.
Great food, and service, impossible to find parking. Valet parking is a must.

Finally got to try this magical place for a birthday celebration with a few friends. We had an exceptionally good evening, which started with one of the most passionate and attentive waiters I have ever had in my life. The many cocktails, appetizers, entrees and desserts which we tried were all fantastic. I can't wait to go back.

Great experience, the cool tower of accoutrements was fantastic. Really liked the chard spinach-y dip and the beet borani. However, the meats (duck and lamb) were a little bit underwhelming. I’ve heard the ribeye is better so will likely return at some point to try it.

The Maydan Thanksgiving take-out menu was one of the brightest spots during a very difficult period.  This may seem over the top, but read on and you'll see why this was one of the most special and delightful experiences we had in 2020.  First, let me say that it was clear an INCREDIBLE amount of thought and planning went into the the meal.  Even other Michelin-level restaurants struggle with how to convert from dine-in to take out during COVID-19.  Maydan has offered the best home dining experience we have seen, bar none, and we cannot imagine one-upping this.  Each item was packaged carefully to keep well (for example, crisp ingredients and sauces separated from other items so nothing would go soggy). Each had impeccable but simple preparation instructions.  Second, the dishes themselves were absolutely stellar.  The rack of lamb was some of the best we've ever tasted, as ardent lamb connoisseurs.  The meat was carefully marinated and vacuum-sealed to keep it fresh, with the perfect amount of sauce and pomegranate molasses required for saucing and crusting.  The cooking time was spot-on for perfect lamb.  The mezze platter and dips were a positive delight, with a plethora of different Middle-Eastern delights to top the pita.  The fennel salad (I think with raddichio and arugulua) was fresh, crisp, and satisfying.  The accompanying brussel sprouts roasted-on-the-stalk made for a striking presentation and went down very well with their sauce. The duck confit fatayer was impeccable and had a beautiful crust.  Third, the the biggest surprise was how generous the Thanksgiving portions were.  It made for a true feast, and we actually managed to get at least 4 full meals for two from the order.  For example, an order for two included an entire salted honey pie (a dish not to be missed!).  This counts doubly when you're aware of just how hard restaurants have had to watch their budgets and food costs during these lean times.   I don't know who gave the nod to these portions, but they're an absolute gem: this was a striking mark of generosity to customers, and a sign of determination to deliver value and ongoing festive delight to customers.  All and all, the Maydan Thanksgiving was a highlight for the year, and I wonder if they might consider something similar even after coronavirus perod passes?  If not, then I hope someone from the Michelin guide had a chance to sample it, because I think a single Michelin Star was selling them short.

I've eaten here once pre-COVID, once during COVID, and once as takeout. This is probably my favorite restaurant in DC. I felt very safe seated outdoors tonight. Their heaters were powerful and the servers were very COVID cautious. The courses and drink pairing were outstanding. The dips and haloumi were out of this world. The duck with sour cherries blew my mind. The lamb shank was perfectly cooked and the delicious sauces made the dish A+. The baklava had flavor but didn't hold together well so dessert left a bit to be desired, especially compared to the other courses. Cocktails and wines were excellent. I can't recommend this place enough. Please visit or do takeout, you won't regret it.
Unbelievable food and top-notch service. The menu is very unique, and everything was delicious. The wine list is really interesting as well.

We also got a seasonal special cocktail in a pitcher cause it was highly recommended, called the Casablanca Cooler! Delicious, light, flavorful. Highly recommend and easy to drink, even though it's mezcal, which many people may not like due to its smokiness. But in this case, it's drowned out by the passionfruit, pear, harissa salt.

From the first moment  you step in that restaurant  the waiters give you a comfortable feeling. Very comfortable waiters, it is a lovely restaurant to hang out with friends or with your date. delicious  food, specialist  chef de cuisine, comfortable  cost and excellent  service. Highly recommended.
Always a delicious meal. One of my favorite restaurants in the DMV.

It was ok. It was ok, and for 50$ a person check it could have been 5 stars place. But it wasn't, it was 1300$, for 5 ppl, on NYE. And for that amount of money, and for the reputation of the place, the expirience was subpar. We were greeted with tea, nice start, which also helped to warm our hands at 38 deg outside. It was then followed by opening dishes - hummus, cabbage salad, chickpeas salad and a salad of nuts and squash with funny name. These dips were accompanied by 4 pita breads, for 6 ppl (??). The salads were very good. Good as my grandma would do? Not so much. Michelin good? I'm not sure, but they were good. After the salads they served us a plate with meat, i want to say it had 8-10 medallions of lamb meat. With a litter bit of couscous, and two plates with mashed potatoes and caramelized onion. It was also good. Not Amazing but def good. After that i asked our waitress what's next? She said that that's it, next are our deserts. Needless to say were disappointed to say, the least. Maydans name is known for food feasts, what we had on the table was more like a wholefoods based quick healthy dinner. A Michelin place, for NYE, serving us salads For deserts we got Baklava. Two plates with two pieces of baklava. That's it. Tea? We had to ask for it, it wasn't even offered. Coffee? Espressos? Never even mentioned. Oh, you want to taste our famous Knaffe? We did not make it for tonight. Sorry. That was the actual conversation between us and our waitress.  To be honest, at this point it was beyond embarrassing, we came there for the food and amazing reputations of the "Maydan's expirience", we left there feeling like we were ripped off. Plain and simple.  We remember this place better, but based on this expirience i could not recommend it to anyone.

New year's eve at Maydan was disappointing, to say the least. The food wad OK minus. Dinner menu (pre fix, not cheap) had 4 cold salads (4 small plates for a table of 6 adults), one main, and one desert. Most of us left the place hungry. The food was generic, non innovative, and basic. The only Shout out is to the waiting staff that was friendly and kind (yet a bit clumsy). I rarely write bad reviews, but this one is well deserved. Will not be back.

One of my favorite spots in DC, hands down! Everything about the atmosphere and interior decoration is perfect. Anyone giving this place anything less than 5 stars needs to have their taste buds examined.

I paid $$$ for a fixed-price Christmas Eve dinner and I couldn't be more disappointed. The food was simple, like the food that you will get in any local resturant on lunch time. Some hummus, garlic paste, carrots and lamb as the main dish. The quantity was ridiculously small... I don't know how in the world this resturant received a Michelin star. I will never come back and will recommend anyone to save the money to a better resturant.

I can't even explain how wonderful and amazing this place is. The ambiance and especially the food, the staff was very welcoming. I have to say that this is the best restaurant I've been to thus far in life. The flavors to each item..wow. Cannot say enough great things about this place! We'll definitely come back.

I've managed to get in several times (be flexible and don't give up-it's worth it). Maydan translates to "a gather place" and it is definitely a place to go with friends or family.

This has to be one of the best restaurants in DC...and if you get the "spread" (ask when you get there) you will be happy enough to be considered giddy.....just sayin...

Completely overrated spot. I’m shook that it has a Michelin Star. Hazel is a much better version of this type of cuisine. All of the lackluster food here is dressed up with pickled onions to make up for the lack of seasoning. We pretty much ordered the whole menu. I’d go back for the halloumi, carrots, sumac lemonade, and sauces. Everything else we ordered (lamb hummus, baba ghanoush, labneh, Aleppo kebab, saffron kebab, ribeye, bread) was like the color beige in the mouth... the meat especially. There are many other restaurants serving this style of food for a fraction of the price. Even Cava is leagues above this place. Overall a disappointing experience.
Phenomenal food, service, and atmosphere. Can’t wait to go back once they open up dining.
Hands down...one of my best foodie experiences ever. And the Obamas were in attendance. So extra cool.
The food is amazing, service was great, the outdoor seating is very socially distancing friendly

It was their first weekend of offering delivery through Tock using Door Dash and it was super convenient. Everything arrived warm and in sturdy containers, in portions that seemed equivalent to what you'd get at the restaurant. We missed the ambience, of course, but because our family is bigger than they could accommodate on the patio with social distancing, it was the next best option to being there in person. They were very hospitable over email while outlining our options. We have eaten here many many times, and this is simply the latest in a string of memorable meals by Maydan. Thank you to all of your staff for working through this pandemic!

I ordered takeout for myself, my husband, my sister and my brother in law. Everything was amazing, all of the sides, dips and vegetables were prepared extremely well and flavorful. They also has the perfect amount of sale. We also got the lamb and whole fish. They were both fine, but the real stars of the meal were the dips and vegetables!

We ordered takeout. Make sure you ask for utensils and napkins if you need them. We ordered the Wednesday special, and it was great. It's a lot of food, so when they say feeds 2-3, believe them!

I finally succumbed to the hype. And that's all this place is. Last Friday, I picked up the lamb, mixed grill, some spreads, one goat shawarma, and left about $230 poorer to feed three people. I mean it was all okay food but not $230 good. I can get similarly good food from Astor Mediterranean for about $50 or even better food from Zaytinya for $100-150. If you want to throw your money away, sure, dine here and lucky you that you can do that during the Great Covidepression. Otherwise, consider going somewhere else. It's just hype and little substance. I have no intention of returning or ordering again. (Caveat: the best thing to do is just order their goat shawarma for $16 and leave. Probably the best thing on the menu and the best value.)

caption: So it's a bit pricey, but worth the experience. The food is very good, excellent spices and well prepared. The service is very good as well. It's more of a family style, share the dish setup. Everything we tried was great, and we had a lot of food! If you're a foodie, this is the experience to put on your list. Only other downside is that it's difficult to get a reservation, so plan ahead...

Maydan is the coolest dining experience in DC. We came in on a walk-in (no reservations) for my fiancés birthday. The service from every point of contact from the host to server to management was outstanding. Our server, Molly treated us like we were old friends and expertly guided us through the menu. The food and the delivery of our food was A+ We can’t wait to return!

UPDATED: I previously reviewed the very annoying reservation experience. Here are my thoughts after actually eating there. Not worth the hype. This is a place to try one time and then be done with it. The head hostess was unwelcoming. Our server was condescending and unhelpful (granted, we overheard other servers and they seemed much better). We were not greeted or thanked as we left the restaurant. The hostess ignored us until we were already out the door and we heard a half-hearted 'thank you.' The food is good, but you'd do much better to go as a group of 4-6 people, as some of the best dishes are "too large for two people." We particularly enjoyed the saffron lamb. The different sauces were pretty good, but nothing absolutely amazing.  BOTTOM LINE: The experience isn't worth the competitive reservation process. Good food and cool atmosphere, although tables are squeezed together. Our experience would have been a lot better if our server had been better, so possibly just some bad luck here.  RESERVATION EXPERIENCE: We received a gift certificate to Maydan for Christmas and we've tried unsuccessfully many times to book a reservation. We're ready to go a little before 10am, but by the time we put in the information it says no tables available. Unfortunately, we have to get a babysitter, so eating at 9:30pm isn't an option and we don't want to risk trying for a bar seat and then not getting one. At this point, I'm still trying for the reservation, but it has been a huge inconvenience and due to the hassle, this would have to be the singularly best meal experience of my entire life in order for me to ever eat there again or recommend it to friends. :( If it weren't for the gift card, I'd have given up a long time ago. So far our experience is a far cry from the "welcoming and warm atmosphere" I've read about.

Beautiful space. Loved the open flame in the middle of the restaurant along with the decor. Wait staff are very knowledgeable and without fail memorized the entire menu. Get the condiments! They're only $1 each and oh so delicious to mix and match with entrees and the fresh naan

Absolutely incredible from the first bite to the last. Try the lamb and you will not regret it. If you dont like spicy food, order the tomato jam as it helps to cut spiciness. Service was out of this world amazing, definitely on my top five list for DC. If you are a fan of fish, you cannot go wrong with the salmon kebab.
This is easily the most fun one star michelin restaurant I have ever been to. From drinks, to atmosphere to food. This is definitely more fun in a group setting than a couples.
One of the best dining experiences I've ever had! Service, food and drinks are all on point.

Overall experience was explanatory. Reservations were booked a month out, I sent an email to see if their was any openings and shortly after I received a confirmation for the date and time I requested! The staff was prompt, knowledgeable, and friendly. The food was authentic and outstanding! I’ve spent a lot of time in the Middle East, North Africa etc.. I’ve experienced very few restaurants  in the states that  are pure as this.  I will be making a reservation in April for May dinner date with the Mrs.
Loved it. The herb plate is a must have addition with any of the spreads. Fantastic restaurant. You will not be disappointed.
Amazing food and outstanding service. Love this place!
Top of the line food and drinks. Unique atmosphere
North african and Mediterranean fusion tastes so much better than it sounds. Along with good service, nice music and great decor Maydan is an experience that's hard to forget.
Very unique decor' and the food was very good as well.  Only negative I would have to say is it almost takes an act of God to get a reservation in this place!!

Food and service were really good. Most dishes are small plate, with the exception of their "large" section. The lamb shoulder was amazing! The atmosphere was lively and in keeping with the "town square"/street theme. You need a reservation, which opens up 30 days in advance.
Great food
Love the open kitchen in this restaurant. Food is great albeit a little expensive.

Recommended by a couple we met in Belize on a recent vacation we were fortunate to get a reservation on Friday night at 7 pm and arrived to find a full house.  Down a back alley you smell the smoke from the open fire pit before you enter through the blue door.  We felt like we were in Morocco. Excellent service, cocktails and food. Unique presentations and just the right amount of spice. Ordered all the condiments as recommended by our server and each was unique and fun to try. Grilled carrots were a highlight (absolute surprise and a must try), muhamarra, lamb hummus, and duck breast were excellent and the bread was the best.
Wow! Five stars for ambiance. Five stars for service. Five stars for food and presentation. Five stars for staff and owner.  This place is perfection

I can be very particular about food and told my wife I wasn't sure if I would like it. She visited here a week earlier and insisted on coming back. I was happy to be wrong about my hesitations.  The atmosphere is tremendous and will take you to a place where you feel like you're in the Middle East. The service was excellent and everyone was very hospitable. I can't say enough about the food, the woodfired taste was unbelievable and the condiments were world class. Highly recommend you try Maydan... 👍🏻

Great food, great service. Guys if you have an online schedule please don't block it, wherever you call or try to make a reservation at any time is always fully booked. If you are always fully booked, don't offer the option to book online where you will never find a table. As much as you want to portrait yourself as busy, is backfiring towards your customers.
Excellent food and the service was phenomenal

I visited Maydan for the first time on a whimsical Wednesday around 5:30 pm. The first come first serve bar seating was already packed but the host set us in up in this quaint corner beneath a staircase.  This place is nothing short of amazing. You meander down an alley, walk into a large, worn door into a small space where you're greeted with smiles and incense smells. If the timing is right for a walk in (reservations recommended) you enter yet another door and it feels like another world.  The sight of the open grill, the music, the knowledgeable service and the DELICIOUS small plates and cocktails really transport you - seriously such an intriguing, unique and warm experience. It feeds all of your senses.  I didn't want to leave Maydan and cannot wait to return!

Has a great menu, super cool vibe, staff were very knowledgeable. The were so friendly, my server Maya was awesome!!. The open grille is so cool, it attacks your senses in the best way. Sizzle smoke, aromatic flavors, flames. It is really a treat. Cocktail menu is really nice, beautifully blended cocktails with delicate flavors. The condiments were very good. The tahini was my favourite, followed by the tomato jam. The hummus is one of the best I've ever tasted anywhere. I highly recommend this restaurant. One thing I didn't like was the independent reservation on an app. That needs looked at and improved. Other then that Maydan is a 10 out of ten.
Good food and great service

Everything is scrumptious and wonderful. Excellent warm and welcoming atmosphere. Great experience. Our server Jessica was an outstanding host. She was very helpful and always there but not overbearing. Very knowledgeable of her wines.The dessert: Shredded kunafa, the cheese should have been milder in taste and consistency. The flavor of the kunafa was perfect.

This Michelin star resteraunt does full justice to your palette. The food is packed with flavour and scrumptious. I love the vibe, service and ambience of the place. If you are a Mediterranean cuisine fan do not miss this place out. I recommend you to book in advance since they running really packed.  My favorites were the Labneh, Sweet Potato, Carrots, Muhamarra, Chermoula with the hot bread that they serve constantly.

Truly a hidden gem in DC. Recently a friend invited me for drinks and small dish at Maydān. I was blown away by the experience. Finding the discrete location was somewhat easy once we found the stunning blue door. Upon entering it was an ordinary experience. The host station was extremely friendly and knowledgeable with the operation (confused host stations are common in DC.) when we entered the main area I was truly surprised. The exposed center cook area was truly an experience I could have watched for hours. REQUEST MAIN SITTING AREA - that’s where the true experience is. The cocktails were great. We passed on light eats as we were not hungry. I will be back soon (once reservations aren’t available.)

Definitely worth the hype. Went here last night (a Thursday) on a whim. Didn't have a reservation, but went at 6:15 and was able to get  seated right away. There were also plenty of spots at the bar! We got the sumac lemonade which was delicious and a great substitute for a cocktail (currently pregnant). My friend got the bourbon cocktail and enjoyed it   We got to sit right  by the open fire! So cool and warm :).  For food we got beet salad, baba ganush (sp??), the sweet potato, halloumi, and saffron lamb, and literally all the dips. I really really really liked the halloumi. Such food flavor. If it went back, I'd probably not do the baba ganush, it was okay but not great like everything else! The sweet potato was also delicious. And the bread they keep at the table is so yummy and great for trying all the dips. Next time I was to try the hummus  and carrots!  Our server recommended getting almost double the amount of food but that would have been way too much. I was definitely full.

Just earned a mich stars this year....they only release a selected number of online bookings. Got there around 4.45 (it open at 5) and there were about 25people already in the line. First got bar seating but then asked and we got a table upstairs. 2hr seating limit.  The food comes out as ready and it’s sharing style.  The place is kinda small, very very meat heavy menu so not much for vegetarians.  They have a big fire pit style oven as u enter which is cool  The lamb leg along was $100 and not sure if it was worth it.  Overall it was an OK meal out
Definitely a restaurant we can recommend for those after an intimate relaxing dinner environment with al fresco option.

I had heard a lot about this place and was eager to try it. I had the Muhamarra (would not recommend), the Halloumi (I wouldn't order it again but it was fine), and the swordfish (would recommend, but it is a very small portion). Service was just ok. Ultimately I left disappointed and felt like this is just another meh DC restaurant, although the interior is different than most restaurants in DC. I wouldn't be opposed to going back but probably wouldn't go out of my way.
The food is absolutely amazing. Had the aleppo, cabbage, sweet potato, a coupe sauces and the labneh wich is out of this world!
Great food, unique layout

MAYDAN is definitely one of my favorite restaurants in Washington DC area. This is such a hidden gem.  From outside, you can hardly notice that this is an actual restaurant. Middle Eastern facade opens up to an amazing cozy space where you check in with the host/hostess. This transition from outside gives you a feeling of a sense of wonder and exploration.Make sure to have reservation in advance. This place is booked months in advance.  Their menu is simply fantastic. The centerpiece of every table is the bread. We were a group of 5 celebrating birthday and we had: Ribeye, Shrimp, Saffron Lamb, Carrots, Labneh all 7 condiments. I loved this place. The owner/operator is the same lady that host “Check, Please DC!” On PBS. The food is progressive and a mix of several different cultures around the Mediterranean Sea. It’s should be on your must visit list of DC restaurants.

I LOVED this place and I am middle eastern! Food was great and very authentic considering we are in the US. It was delicious and nicely plated.  Plates are great to share.  My most favorite part was their ambiance and a great playlist that I'm now listening to! Highly recommended.

We didn't know if we were in the right place, and once we find the door we had no idea if it was open. However, one we walked in we realized this place was packed and for good reason. Maydan was a beautiful restaurant with a great atmosphere and even better food. Do yourself a favor and get all of the sauces for your bread... You won't regret it

The dinner was nothing short of an experience. Very unique and beautiful space. The hummus and eggplant spread were delicious, we tried all of the sauces. I would recommend the tenderloin over the lamb which was a little chewy. My only feedback would be that our server recommended 7-8 dishes for 2 people which was much too many. I think 4 or 5 would have been enough. Thanks!
Great for the dips alone!
Amazing food...
Great food, service and atmosphere.
The service and food at Maydan is unparalleled. Even if when I haven't had a reservation, being polite and arriving early enough in the evening, I've always been served.
Could not recommend this place higher. Small sharable plates that are great for parties of all sizes. Don't miss out on the condiments, they are amazing with the endless bread they provide the table

Loved the food here. The flavour profile is so satisfying that its hard to stop eating. Economical is the second word that comes to mind after dinning here which is something not synonymous with a michelin star restaurant.  There are some things that could definitely improve though. The comfort of seating could be improved, I had to ask the host to chage our seat at first. Their high rise tables are weird and you would find yourself sitting in an awkward position. On the food front, everything but the bread is good. the bread could be improved a lot. But, nevertheless thes place does deserve to be visted again if and only if you could manage to get a reservation.
Food is delicious and service is good, too.

Walking into Maydan is a little like being magically transported to another country. It is so beautiful and overwhelmingly authentic. Our service was exceptional to the point where it was almost funny how prompt our server was and how quickly they refilled our waters. The beverages were fabulous. The food was beyond good. I’ve never enjoyed carrots so much in my life. Don’t miss the ribeye, lamb hummus and ALL OF THE SAUCES. Yum yum yum!

We sat at the bar, and Hunter was an excellent guide on what to order.  Everything we ate was amazing, but by far our favorite choice was the charred sweet potato.  The vibrant atmosphere with the fire pit in the middle was spectacular!

Great food. I highly recommend the duck. Awesome atmosphere. The only complaint I have was that the waitress was too pushy, telling us we didn't order enough, even tho we had leftovers at the end of the meal.

Our server Laura was awesome, she made great recommendations for our group which had people with dietary restrictions. The quality of the food is great but the portions are a bit small, but definitely worth it. Highly recommend trying the swordfish which seems like a sleeper on their menu. The atmosphere made the experience enjoyable as well. Had a bit of a mishap with a drink order but Laura was very accommodating and offered to take it back for a change.

This was the kind of meal so amazing that it makes me question every other five star review I’ve left. I was with a group of three and we ordered the halumi, eggplant, swordfish, sweet potato, Aleppo lamb, tenderloin, and a bunch of dips. The swordfish was perfect, seared crispy but still buttery inside. The cocktails were great, especially the not-too-sweet pistachio tree. Dessert was fine but not as outstanding as the rest of the meal. We arrived 15 minutes after they opened and only got a table for the first seating because a reservation cancelled. Highly recommend getting there right when they open if you want to snag a seat at the bar

What an incredible meal!  What I ate: - Hummus: OMG! This was hands down, the BEST hummus I've ever had. Super creamy, flavorful. I just kept dipping more pieces of bread into the hummus - Labneh: This was also flavorful and a nice creamy contrast to our dishes - Duck breast: We saw another table order this and HAD to order it. It was perfectly cooked, tender, flavorful. - Tenderloin: This was delicious and tender, but probably the sad middle child of all the dishes we ordered. I can't complain about the dish, but it was missing the sharp wow the other dishes brought - Zucchini: That zatar seasoning on top really packed a flavor punch. Zucchini was perfectly cooked, not too mushy, still very fresh and flavorful - Shrimp: Wow! I wouldn't say that this was spicy, but it packed a strong flavor. I loved it. Not over cooked at all. - Tahini: To be honest, this was kind of unremarkable. While flavorful, it tasted too similar to the hummus that I didn't use much of this dipping sauce. - Tomato Jam: This was bright and acidic - Chermoula: This reminded me of chimichurri and it was nice bright herby flavor  Pros: - What a gem! The restaurant entrance is hidden in an alley, with no recognizable sign on the door. Very mysterious. Once you check in with the hostess, you are lead to enter into the main dining room through another door. The layers of doors and clandestine entryways make it very magical - Food: I really cannot emphasize how amazing our meal was. That fresh bread! OMG soooo good. I would have been happy with the hummus and bread. My friend and I initially just went in to grab a cocktail and a snack before getting dinner elsewhere, but ended up coming back a few hours later for a late dinner, because the food was THAT good. - That fresh baked bread. OMG so good. Carb me up! - Thankful to the staff who were able to squeeze us in for a late reservation and accommodate us. - Cocktails were delightfully refreshing - Wine list was interesting with wines from regions my friend and I were not familiar with - Beautiful dining room. The dramatic central fire pit is the central point, with a long dramatic bar along one side of the room. With the fire pit in the center, you can't help but be mesmerized by the cooks working to tame the fire to make your meal. We sat upstairs for our meal and were able to get a nice view of the bar below - Price is right! It was a very reasonably priced meal considering the amount of food ordered, as well as a bottle of wine.  Cons: - Hard to get a rez! Every time a rez would open up on opentable, by the time I clicked the link in the email, that reservation was already gone - Despite the allure and magical entrance, it was a TAD confusing trying to locate the restaurant since the entrance is in an alleyway - Since it's a small space that is trying to pack as many people in, the tables are kind of tight, as is the bar  Would I come again? Yes!

Not surprising this place deserves 5 stars. I’d give it another one if there were six. I felt like I escaped the cold weather and hectic pace of work and life for a few hours with the fire going and new tastes and special drinks - and the irony was I was there for a work event!
Phenomenal venue and cuisine. A lovely spot for a private event, too.

Had an excellent anniversary dinner here the other night! Yes, I was one of the crazy people who booked a table here a month in advance and yes, I did set my alarm so I could get on right at 10 am to make the reservation.  From the moment I walked into this place, I felt like I was out of DC and in Morocco or some other Middle Eastern place. The fire pit where they cook all the food is in full display on the bottom floor. We were seated on the second floor and started with the hummus (smoothest hummus ever!) and the bread they kept bringing out during the meal was to die for.  We also ordered the carrots, sweet potato, duck and lamb. Everything was tasty and the condiments were also really good. The tomato jam was especially delicious on the duck, which was seared perfectly.  We ordered the cheesecake for dessert which was another A+ choice.  Would definitely come back. Great dining experience.
My favorite restaurant in DC. Never disappoints.
Outstanding. Great service too. Must experience.

Our table wasn't ready at our reservation time because the guests before us were taking a bit longer than expected, so we were graciously offered cocktails on the house and we barely had to wait 5 more minutes before we were sat. The manager on duty that night who accommodated us (Nov 4) was beyond excellent, she came to check in on us several times that night. The food was delightful too.

Everything on the menu is delicious. The staff will recommend a certain amount of dishes for a full meal and I completely agree with their suggestion (honestly can't remember what they said). It is a very share-friendly menu with something for everyone. Recommend getting all of the condiments ($1 each)

great atmosphere, and service, and the cocktails are fabulous. The food is incredibly good too the halloumi was a stand out. Perfect combo of salty and sweet. I’ve lived in the middle east for three years... this definitely stacks up. But maybe skip the lamb skewers if you don’t like fatty, gristly meat. It was a bit of a let down.

This place is a scam. Let’s start with the entrance which looks like a dirty night club. In terms of food, they serve samples only. If you ate thinking to eat a full meal then this is the wrong place for you. The place is very crowded and the style is ugly. This IS NOT a middle eastern restaurant by any chance. There are so many Resturants in DC that are much better. Don’t come to this place unless you want to be scammed.

One of my favorite DC dining experiences in the last year. Great service with exceptional food and wine.  Best hummus I’ve had in the area but the highlight is the ribeye.  Expertly seasoned and grilled to perfection.  Their dips worked really well with the steak.  Will be back soon to try more of the menu.

The food is outstanding !, ...but there is clearly a lack of Management attention to service.  On our most recent visit: 1.  The restaurant left me and others out in the rain for 20 minutes waiting to get inside to book a walk-in reservation. 2.  We were given a 7:15 pm reservation and asked if they'd text us when the table was ready -- they said no just come back at 7:15.  We did not get seated until 30+ minutes later and had to wind up finding a corner of the first floor to huddle in for the 30 minutes with no area to stand or be out of the way. 3.  Several ordered items were never brought to the table, we had to chase down wait staff. 4.  All of the small plates we ordered with the Lamb shoulder were delivered 20+ minutes before the Lamb.  There was no effort made to apologize for the service issues or offer a dessert or take an item off the bill as a gesture.  No one item is a big deal in and of itself ... but Maydan prides itself as a Michelin star restaurant and the service needs to better match the outstanding food.
Amazing service and delicious food!
Food is great but the fumes and smell from the oven in the middle was too much to take. I had watery eyes all through dinner.
Just a magical place with amazing food.

Love the ambience and the hummus choices! Could use a few more filling vegetarian options though. Just hummus and naan make you feel like you are leaving a bit hungry.  Everything tasted awesome though!

Bit overrated, food was okay, but served cold. Drinks were fantastic and atmosphere was probably the best. I would wait for the fab to pass and then go... otherwise not worth waiting 30 minutes of waiting.
This was an experience.  The food was different, but delicious.  You really do ger full.
Amazing flame-grilled meats and dipping sauces! Small venue with awesome ambiance and drinks. Sit at the bar is your only hope without a reservation.
I thought this was a really excellent meal. And very good value for money. Sat at the bar. Good cocktails and excellent food and atmosphere. Memorable.
Great service great space great food great drinks! Make a reservation.
Outstanding service and unusual flavors in eclectic environment.  Cool grafitti art in bathroom too!
Fantastic!
What an amazing culinary experience. Everything was absolutely delicious. The restaurant deserves 6/5 stars. It is definitely worth going with a group and doing the prefix  menu.

Wow wow wow wow wow  From the minute you walk in you know you’re in an awesome spot. Upbeat music with bass and an open wood fire grill are the first things to catch your attention. The food was dope.

The women working the door were slightly racist, and the food was underwhelming at best. Some of the meat was seriously undercooked. We couldn't believe we waited a month to visit this overhyped restaurant.
Lived up to the hype in that, they have amazing food and wonderful staff. Romantic lighting and fast service.
Amazing flavors. Great service, cool relaxed vibe. Best sweet potato I have ever had.

If you’re allergic to honey it’s not for you. A colleague was excited to bring us here and we made provisions in advance for my allergy but yet so many dishes (including the bread) still contained this ingredient that it really ruined the experience for me. I should add that I’ve dealt with this allergy my entire life and have traveled the world without it ever being such an issue... And I’ve never been given a slice of raw red cabbage as a substitute for freshly baked bread. Kinda weirdly off-putting. I also felt everything was over-spiced. Having recently moved out of Williamsburg maybe I’m just over places that I feel try too hard to be relevant. But my colleagues had a great time and some even said it was their favourite DC food experience so to each their own.

This place is hard to get into, but it's worth making the reservation in advance.We split a ton of vegetables, dips, and sides as a table, and got the whole roast chicken as the centerpiece. Spices and flavors were absolutely delicious, and the waitress was helpful in telling us what would pair well with what. The atmosphere of the building is amazingly cool as well, with the incredibly chic restaurant hidden behind a door (with no sign) halfway down a seemingly random alley. A huge fire pit in the center of the first floor is just one feature of the eclectic and cool atmosphere. You've got to go see it (and, of course, taste it) for yourself.
The best restaurant in Washington no doubt ❤️❤️
Delicious, exotic, flavorful, friendly, different.

Definitely lived up to the hype and exceeded our expectations. Probably the coolest most unique atmosphere I've dined in and some of the best food ever.  A very special place that I could not recommend more highly.
Ridiculously good in every respect.
Food and service were excellent!
Good luck getting reservation tho
The service was great, our server was very knowledgeable about all the items on the menu. The food is good, you are definitely in for an experience.
Awesome atmosphere extremely friendly staff. Delicious food. A great dinner experience.

Washington's new hot restaurant---they just got their Michelin star in September 2019, so you have to call well ahead for reservations, which we didn't have, so we tried for the bar seats. The place is down the alley from Florida Ave.: there's a small sign  but their actual door seems to be unmarked. We walked in and waited near the bar, which fortunately didn't take too long. The place was obviously pretty full and the house music was quite loud. The ambiance is pretty  inviting, with the open fire bread ovens right in the middle of the room. Beirut hummus with their bread is a treat; I liked their vegetable dishes. The Aleppo lamb kebab was very flavorful but if I was making it I would add some sauce or fillings to make it less dry. I'm looking forward to try their seafood in the future.
Maydan has a special place in my heart - everything on the menu is divine!
Great atmosphere and quality of good

Fantastic! Tasty food, great atmosphere and hospitable staff. Love it!!!! The condiments were sublime with the bread. Everything we had was on point: the chickpeas, the eggplant dip, the barramundi, shrimp, etc. Glad we saved room for dessert too!

Amazing dishes, super delicious food! Atmosphere and Ambiance is neat, comfortable and elegant. Amazing with the huge grill in the middle and the open fire! The restaurant appears super clean. Servers are pleasant, communicative, efficient and knowledgeable. And most importantly the food is nicely presented, taste was delicious to a good price point. I can highly recommend to order all the condiments and the eggplant tomato dip!
Its looks so cool. I want to eat there.
Good energetic atmosphere, great service, and great food.
Can't believe how good this food, atmosphere, and staff are. Honestly the best food I have had in DC in 20 years of living here. Definitely need to book reservations well ahead of time!

The food was all amazing. Of the meat that we had, the tenderloin skewers were wonderful. The beiruiti hummus had us getting a second order of it once the first was devoured. The labneh was very tart and tangy. Bread was resupplied all night. The condiments were all fantastic as well. I'd go back any time. One of the best dining experiences that I have had in DC.

We've heard great things about Maydan and were finally able to secure a reservation last Saturday evening. We sat fairly close to the wood fire kitchen and was able to get a good show of the chefs' magic happening. We ordered the halloumi and several dips to start, all delicious, especially the eggplant one. Love the generously sized pieces of eggplant within the spread. We also ordered several dips to go with our meal - our favorites were the harissa and toum, though the tomato jam was delicious with bread. We ordered several meats to share including the rib eye, duck, and lamb kabobs. The meat colors were a gorgeous cool red center - cooked perfectly. The duck was probably the best duck any of us have ever had. Please don't take it off the menu!! The rib eye was flavorful and tender, and the kabob was full of seasonings/flavor. We ended the meal by trying all 3 dessert options available. The cheesecake and almond cakes were delicious but the apricot cream one wasn't good. Please add coffee to the menu, would be a great complement. Our server Laura was also super animated and passionate about the menu and explaining everything. Thanks for a wonderful experience all around, we'll definitely be back!

Everything on the menu is delicious. The staff will recommend a certain amount of dishes for a full meal and I completely agree with their suggestion (honestly can't remember what they said). It is a very share-friendly menu with something for everyone. Recommend getting all of the condiments ($1 each)
Amazing food, great wine selection (try the skin contact wines). Cozy little spot that's tough to get a reservation for, but well worth the wait.
Really fun restaurant. Very interesting dinner options. Great bread.
Liked this place way more the second time at the bar versus a table.  Very good spreads. Had the tenderloin which was excellent.

Made a reservation on RESERVE about a month in advance to get a prime dining time.  FAVORITES: Halloumi - salty, nutty and sweet Toum - creamy, garlicky and texture of butter Bread - nice crusty outside and thick chewy center  JUST OK: Seasonal Fatoush - crisp bread, tomatoes, radish,  sumac vinaigrette *basic salad, crisp bread was soggy Beiruti Hummus - tomatoes, parsley, green peppers, scallions *very watery for hummus I really prefer a thicker texture Beet Borani: yogurt, dill, black sesame *really sweet, texture was very watery, black sesame didn't add to dish, it looked better than it tasted Shrimp: *this is the worst value at $18 u get 4.5 shrimp, I say .5 bc they gave us a really small piece of shrimp and there was no marinade or flavor whatsoever Ribeye: *there was a nice spice rub on it and the meat was cooked to a nice medium and was a large portion but it felt like a lower quality meat, obviously not as good as a ribeye from a steakhouse  CONDIMENTS: (In the order in which I liked them) Toum: garlic, oil, lemon, egg whites *creamy, garlicky and texture of butter Chermoula: lemon, garlic, parsley, saffron *this went well with the shrimp since that had no flavor Ezme: tomato, onion, peppers, pomegranate molasses *our server described this as middle eastern salsa pretty accurate Tomato Jam: sesame, cinnamon *very sweet didn't really go with anything Zhough: parsley, cilantro, cumin, Serrano *nearly choked from the spice of the Serrano  WINE LIST: Pretty extensive list with red, white, rose, skin contact and sparkling wines by the glass.  We tried the skin contact wines which remind me of a rose but with a slightly sour/bitter finish.  SERVICE/ATMOSPHERE: Our server was really attentive and provided great recommendations.  It is very loud so you really speak loud to hear each other.  It's also very dark and very hot so wear less clothing.  The tables are really small considering their dishes are a lot of small plates so we ran out of room on the table.  The only criticism I have is the bread service I wish they brought one per person at the beginning of the meal because we ran out quickly and then the condiments weren't really used once the bigger items came along and then they gave us bread when we didn't want any.  Menu online is outdated as well, probably about 4 months old, cmon update that!  I never understand when restaurants don't update that at least once a month.

I almost never ever provide a bad review, but Maydan deserves a bad review. How can this place be so highly rated? It’s a run of the mill Mediterranean spot, which isn’t a bad thing, but it’s not a top 100 place is DC of a best new restaurant in DC.  We got the muhamarra, dango, halloumi, roasted peppers (special), condiments, shrimp, and tenderloin. Only the special was decent. The halloumi (which I love) was completely forgettable. The tenderloin was overly salted. The shrimp? Overcooked and chewy. The bread they serve was good but is it served to mask the deficiencies elsewhere? The cocktails were supremely weak. I could keep going on.  We waited for a month to come here (after failing to get reservations otherwise). An anniversary dinner that we will remember only for the let down that the food was.  Save your money and go to better places in DC. Rooster and owl, chiko, rasika, daikaya, red hen, salt line. All much much better than maydan. Maydan overhypes and under delivers.

Very nice middle eastern style bar/restaurant. Very well decorated with beautiful doors. The food was simply delicious. The lamb shoulder is tender and moist. The food is cooked on cast iron pans in the center of the restaurant over a wood fire. It gets busy, so a reservation is strongly recommended. For first timers, the entrance is somewhat hard to find, down an alley, just look for the gorgeous middle eastern door.
Such a cool spot!  Great cocktails and great service along with some of the best food I have ever had.  The lamb shoulder was to die for!
Everything we ate was great. We had a large party and did a chef picked meal. So much food.
Food and place is over rated, for the prize and the wait to make reservation that long definetly not worth it.
Laura was amazing. The food was delicious.
Nice place staff very friendly,food great.
Amazing atmosphere. Love the decoration and the big fire pit !! Food is great !! Highly recommend the duck !! Also, they have wine for my home country Tunisia that I recommend.😉.
Great atmosphere

A magical place tucked away in U street. The Maydan space is intriguing, cozy, with a lot of attention to detail - the laguiole knives, Tunisian napkins..We were lucky to get a cozy corner with a view of the raging fire, over which our lamb shoulder slowly dripped to deliciousness. Everything we tried was unique and delicious - all the deserts were great, though the one with apricot and pistachio was even better. Eager to go back and try everything we didn’t have enough room on our table or in our bellies for! Great work folks!
Certainly an enjoyable experience for dinner.
Outstanding to say the least. Great dinner experience.
Extraordinarily tasty

Maydan definitely lives up to the hype. Came from out of town and would definitely come back for the amazing food and service. The condiments are worth the splurge and the whole chicken is crispy like a Chinese roasted duck. Was a great experience and value.

I was in DC for vacation and was in the mood for Mediterranean. Maydan was highly recommended online, so we hopped a bus over. This was a Thursday night at around 7pm. This is a prime time for happy hours in DC, so I expected to wait. They told us about a two hour wait for a table, but we can wait for two spots to open at the bar if we stand near it. We opted for this option.  My only negative, that kind of leaves a bad taste in your mouth, is that when they open the door for you to walk in and wait, there is next to nowhere to stand really. We stood next to the open stove, which was insanely hot, so my mom and I stood to the right side of the door for awhile to stay out of the walkway. There is no space to stand or else you're in the walkway, in front of the open stove getting cooked, or standing too close to the tables behind you. We felt like unwanted stepchildren. Therefore, it is up to you to keep your mental note about your place in "line" for grabbing a barseat.  When a couple of ladies got up to leave, this man and his date slid in the chair as we were going for them. I notified him that we were next, and he spoke loudly and rudely saying "I ASSURE you that we were here first".   I walked back out to the waitstaff and asked if we were there before them, and they did confirm that we were there first. They kindly apologized on their behalf...but don't expect them to assert authority within their own establishment...However, we were notified a little later that there was a table that freed up (since a group cancelled their reservations), so we scored a nice private table about 30 minutes later.  The food was delicious. I loved everything except the carrots. The carrots could have stood to have more flavor for the price. They weren't very cooked either. I do recommend the restaurant for it's food, environment, and waitstaff, but I wouldn't recommend it if you have abandonment issues and no reservation lol. They could stand to re-utilize the space in a manner that is more functional for those waiting for seats/tables.

This came at a recommendation of a friend who was leaving DC soon!  He mentioned it was one of the restaurants that he wanted to try before me moved and tried many times to get a reservation, but failed.  Well I suggested, why don't we just go and wait for a walk-in?  We did that and to our luck, we were able to snatch a table for two at the bar right when the restaurant opened!  Yay!  Very cool interior, a bit small and tight, but perfect for a date night!  The bar can be a little hot because there is a large fire in the middle of the dining room.  That's where the check cooks on the open fire and grill.  Food was either a hit or a miss!  I really loved the warm pita bread that is constantly refilled throughout your meal!  Definitely get the spreads and try many of them, I thought those were the best!  I will highly recommend getting the Toum!  It was so garlicky and delicious with the warm pita! Basically ate that ALL night! haha.  Another recommendation is the carrots with harissa!  Yum!  I also ordered the duck, which was just cooked too raw and hard to chew.  I'd suggest a pass on that.  Drinks here were so good! Something I'd do is come get drinks and eat spreads with pita.  That will be a perfect meal for me! haha.

Food was good but I feel the food is a little overrated for the time it took to get reservations. I don't think there are a lot of Mediterranean restaurants around so people are excited to try but nothing I'm dying to go to in the near future. The plates are small so definitely order a variety of dishes. The ambiance was really nice
Amazing!

Amazing, had a lucky chance to go. We dug in like we haven't eaten in weeks and it disappeared like crazy. I would highly recommend it to anyone I know. The more people the merrier! It's a place where you should definitely split dishes. I would die for the man who brought us the bread. The dessert is also worth it, it hit the spot perfectly.

It takes a while to put an order in but seems like a great place for reservations and/or regulars. Everything is delicious as long as you can be patient. Staff is friendly but seemed stretched a bit thin.
All I can say is, YOU HAVE TO TRY THIS PLACE! Amazing food and service.

This place is hard to get into, but it's worth making the reservation in advance.We split a ton of vegetables, dips, and sides as a table, and got the whole roast chicken as the centerpiece. Spices and flavors were absolutely delicious, and the waitress was helpful in telling us what would pair well with what. The atmosphere of the building is amazingly cool as well, with the incredibly chic restaurant hidden behind a door (with no sign) halfway down a seemingly random alley. A huge fire pit in the center of the first floor is just one feature of the eclectic and cool atmosphere. You've got to go see it (and, of course, taste it) for yourself.
Great food and atmosphere, definitely want to go back

This was my second visit to Maydan. It’s a lovely restaurant that truly transports you. Great service but I have to say a little underwhelming food wise. The kebabs we ordered-  lamb and tenderloin - were grisly. That’s not what we would expect from such a celebrated restaurant. Hopefully a one off but for that only 3 stars.

This place it’s absolutely amazing! It brings middle eastern culture and flavor in each bite!! The place it’s self, design, atmosphere, the music it’s fantastic and one of the best food I have tried n the city! And Jess at the bar, she goes above and beyond to provide excellent customer service!! I usually don’t drink but I will  recommend “my religion it’s love”  it was a delicious drink we tried at Maydan!
This place is outstanding. If you have one night to eat in DC, make it Maydan.
Amazing food, especially the meats. At at the bar and the staff was super helpful and friendly!
Very very special dining experience. The kind of quality and service you can only get in a big city in a wealthy nation.
Delicious Georgian cuisine. Menu changes seasonally which keeps me wanting more with such a variety of dishes. We live nearby so we go often for the beet borani dip and great cocktails.
Is nice place

Great place and wonderful food. Went the other night and we had the duck, the swordfish kebab, the spinach and labneh spread and the chickpea dish as well as a few dips. Everything was great and full of flavor. We also got the zucchini which was good but compared to the others, could be skipped. The food comes out pretty quickly and the service is good as well. Overall the favorites were the duck(pictured) and the swordfish. They were out of the lamb when we went but we want to try that out next time. It is down an alley so it was a but hard to find at first.

Our family was in DC for the Easter weekend. We dined with a party of 8 people. We were served a fabulous preset menu , which seemed to include “everything on the menu” !!There wasn’t anything that we ate that I wouldn’t order again! The food was served family style with bright fragrant sauces with every courses . The grilled ribeye and the lamb shoulder were both “over the top” delicious. The service was wonderful . I would highly recommend.

We loved Maydan. The vibe was wonderful with the kitchen in the center and the bar at one side. The waitperson was terrific: high energy, funny, and totally helpful. The bread is amazing as are the spreads. The beans were wonderful and the whole cauliflower was delicious. I can’t list everything we ate but it was all just wonderful.

(Translated by Google) The pita bread very rich. The place is very special with an oven in the middle. The service very attentive. I will be back.  (Original) El pan de pita muy rico. El local es muy especial con un horno en medio. El servicio muy atento. Volveré.
The rare gem that exceeds the hype. Excellent food, cool ambiance, and great service. Order as many dips as possible!

Though it can be hard to get reservations, this place is well worth the process and it's praise. We highly recommend the saffron lamb, all the sauces, and the duck. The sauces with garlic and tomato jelly were incredible. Gotta check it out!

We were nestled high on the mezzanine,W not in direct view of the fire, but made several excuses  as to why we had to go exploring the smaller than expected space. Our server was very knowledgeable and thorough and we ended up with a not-overwhelming selection of food a wonderfully paired red wine. The special was goat shoulder and we had a healthy portion of leftovers. In the end, one of the most memorable dining experiences in DC.

Absolutely amazing!!! Maydan's name has been floating around the city for sometime and supper difficult to get a reservation but please believe the hype!! It's a total experience as if you have entered another country! If you are in need of a vacation add this to the list but pack your patience if you don't have a reservation. Tucked away in a alley off FL ave once you see the detailed door you have made it. My friend and I didn't have a reservation but decided to take a chance around 6pm. Truly a unique culinary experience with an open flame kitchen that adds a sizzling charcoal flavor and memorizing to watch! Fun cultural immersion with dishes influenced by different regions in the Middle East -  Lebanon, Georgia, Iran, Morocco, etc. We enjoyed endless rounds of fluffy bread, savory dips peppered with spices, and veggies bursting with flavor.  I love how the servers come around with warm scrumptious bread right out of the Georgian clay oven! The wood-fired oven truly makes a difference and gives the bread a nice charred crust. The bread is much better than the pita at Zaytinya and more savory than naan. It's made of  white and wheat dough, salt, and honey. Apparently, it's the only wood-fired Georgian oven in the U.S.  I recommend getting a variety of dips, condiments, veggies, and dishes to share. They pair really well together with complementary flavors and go hand-in-hand with the bread!  My favorite dishes were the Halloumi Cheese, Turnips, Beiruti Hummus, Chermoula and Tahina dips, and Apple Cheesecake.  The seared Halloumi Cheese was delicious topped with peanuts, sesame, and honey. I love the texture of the cheese and how it doesn't melt.  The Turnips coated with Tahina sauce was the star among the veggies. I knew never turnips could be so tasty! The sweet potato was fun to try, but a bit too sweet from the brown sugar. Although I enjoyed the carrots, the spicy Harissa sauce was a bit tangy for me.  Of the 3 spreads we ordered, the Beiruti Hummus was my favorite. Although I was tempted to get the classic Hummus, I'm glad I ventured out and got the Beiruti. The extra veggies - tomato, scallions, parsley, and green peppers elevated the hummus. I wasn't a fan of the Zaalouk charred eggplant or the overly sweet Muhumarra with pomegranate molasses and red pepper.  I recommend trying some of the Condiments (they are worth the $1!) Of the 3 dips, I enjoyed the Chermoula with lemon, saffron, garlic, parsley and also the Tahina with sesame, lemon, and olive oil. The sauces paired well together and great for dipping the bread! I wasn't a big fan of the Toum - a heap of garlic.  Let's not forget dessert! The Granny Smith Apple Compote Cheesecake was divine! Refreshing to see a modern twist on the traditional slice of cheesecake. I love the creamy whipped pudding texture with apple compote and graham cracker crust. We savored every last bite with no crumbs spared.  If your are looking for a light refreshing cocktail - get the Marrakesh Mule! It tastes like a Moscow Mule with a Middle Eastern twist - the cardamom adds a nice kick. I wasn't a fan of the MEA (Middle Eastern Airlines) cocktail, Arak liquor has a bold black liquorice flavor. The server was really nice and swapped it out for the Marrakesh Mule.  The only thing that was bizarre and caught my attention was why the check was in an Arabic or Urdu Sacred Text book. I was told there was no religious affiliation with the restaurant. Given the respect of cultures and passion for food, why is the check presented in a sacred text? I don't get it.  As someone whose not a big fan of Michelin star restaurants, Maydan is well worth the hype and tenacious search for a reservation 3 weeks in advance! If you have a late reservation at 9:15, order your food quickly as the kitchen shuts down at 10.  While the food is pricey at $10 for a small tapas dish, the ambiance and  communal dining experience is worth it! Maydan takes the open kitchen concept to another level and delivers on its promise for a cultural immersion. If you are ready to venture, push open the cast iron door!

I am always both pleased and surprised when a restaurant surpasses the hype and delivers a unique experience that will definitely be something I repeat. We visited Maydan on a sunday night, with reservations for a party of four.  (I do suggest making a reservation, although you can get lucky if there is a cancellation - or if there is space at the bar).  The reservation system can be tricky, as this is not a large venue and it is popular. We lingered at the bar before being seated, as this restaurant has really nice decor (I took a lot of pictures) and an open, wood fired grill/oven) that is a centerpiece of the downstairs seating area. We were seated fairly quickly, and the drink and food selections were unique and delicious.  I strongly urge you to ask the server about the menu, as this is not a typical middle eastern restaurant. We tried all the sauces (under $10 for all of them) and enjoyed them with the ample house-made Pita breads.  only 2 were spicy, and all were tasty. The food came out as it was cooked, and I must endorse the carrots, the beets, the baked cheese, the Chicken (a must have, it comes with sauce, although it is marvelous plain).  The Lamb was a  smaller,  tasting portion, and equally well prepared and delightful.  We did not have the salads, but I can only imagine that they are equally as good. The owner did greet us, and explain that Maydan was a traditional "gathering  or eating space, where people meet".   She was passionate about her restaurant and  wanted to make sure our experience was satisfactory.  I was impressed with her excitement about what she does, and her challenges in meeting everyone's expectations.  IMHO, she does a great job and has a well trained and equally passionate staff. Our experience was wonderful and this is truly a restaurant experience worth repeating. Parking is tough around the restaurant, so I recommend an Uber or mass transit.  The restaurant is in an alley, look for the sign on the corner of the building so you don't wander around.  Handicapped access is doable but may be difficult, and the alley is set back from the street. When you come to Maydan,  leave any preconceived ideas at the door.  This is a non-typical but not over-reaching venue.  Try the wine, or their house special mixed drinks, and live in the moment.  Enjoy!

I had high hopes for the service after reading a write-up in Food & Wine, but we had a waitress that must have been having an off day because she could not have been less interested in her job that evening and offered no information about the dining style. Their menu has a list of spreads and condiments and just looking at the menu you can tell they are meant to play a larger role in the meal than most restaurants. It's tapas style and they bring naan constantly (never-ending naan is always a good thing). Given the cuisine they feature spice also tends to be a factor. Having said all of that, it's helpful for the wait staff to advise the average size of the dishes (since some tapas restaurants have larger portions than others), give a few thoughts on the dips and condiments and advise the portion size for both, and to mention the constant supply of naan so you don't order a ton of dishes not realizing a large portion of the meal is automatically provided. There is a separate group of the wait staff that is responsible for keeping your water full and naan stocked and they did a great job. The food was good enough that I will consider going back; I assume our waitress was not a representation of their overall wait staff.
